    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/2503.01986v3</id>
    <title>Adaptively profiling models with task elicitation</title>
    <updated>2025-09-25T23:09:21Z</updated>
    <link href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.01986v3" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/>
    <link href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.01986v3" rel="related" type="application/pdf" title="pdf"/>
    <summary>Language model evaluations often fail to characterize consequential failure modes, forcing experts to inspect outputs and build new benchmarks. We introduce task elicitation, a method that automatically builds new evaluations to profile model behavior. Task elicitation finds hundreds of natural-language tasks -- an order of magnitude more than prior work -- where frontier models exhibit systematic failures, in domains ranging from forecasting to online harassment. For example, we find that Sonnet 3.5 over-associates quantum computing and AGI and that o3-mini is prone to hallucination when fabrications are repeated in-context.</summary>
